Keep CPU debug logic powered so PMCCNTR_EL0 / PMU event counters tick.

Background
==========
On RK3399 the PMU (Performance Monitoring Unit) and the cycle counter
PMCCNTR_EL0 live inside the per-core *debug* power domain. After cold
boot bits DBG_NOPWERDWN_L*_EN / DBG_NO_PWERDWN_B*_EN in PMU_SFT_CON
(offset 0x24) are 0, which lets the chip-level PMU controller gate the
debug logic together with the core whenever BL31 manages CPU power.
Result: from non-secure EL2/EL1 the cycle counter reads back the value
written to it, but never increments.

Symptoms (without this patch, on H-Exo bare-metal kernel @ EL2):
    [PMU] DBGAUTHSTATUS=0x000000FF (NSNID=3)        ; debug authorised
    [PMU] DIAG2 CurEL=0x8 sentinel_rb=0xDEADBEEFCAFE0000
    [PMU] DIAG  PMCR=0x41033041 CNTENSET=0x8000003E cyc_delta=0x0
    PMU_PWRDN_ST after=0x00 (CHANGED from 0x3E)     ; BL31 powered the
                                                     ; debug domain off

Fix
===
In plat_rockchip_pmu_init() (executed once during BL31 cold boot)
explicitly set DBG_NOPWERDWN_L0..L3_EN and DBG_NO_PWERDWN_B0..B1_EN
in PMU_SFT_CON. This tells the chip-level PMU to keep CPU debug
logic clocked even when the core power domain is being managed,
which is exactly what we want for non-invasive performance counting
from the OS side. PSCI core-on/off behaviour is unaffected: cores
themselves are still gated normally; only the debug subsystem
(containing PMCCNTR / event counters) stays powered.

Apply from TF-A root (tag v2.14.x), path:
plat/rockchip/rk3399/drivers/pmu/pmu.c

--- a/plat/rockchip/rk3399/drivers/pmu/pmu.c
+++ b/plat/rockchip/rk3399/drivers/pmu/pmu.c
@@ -1620,6 +1620,21 @@ void plat_rockchip_pmu_init(void)
 
 	init_pmu_counts();
 
+	/*
+	 * Keep per-core debug power domain alive so that PMCCNTR_EL0 and
+	 * the PMU event counters keep ticking when non-secure software
+	 * (EL2/EL1) reads them. Without this, the PMU registers are
+	 * read/writeable but their input clock is gated together with
+	 * the core power domain, freezing the cycle counter at whatever
+	 * value it last held. Bits live in PMU_SFT_CON (offset 0x24).
+	 */
+	mmio_setbits_32(PMU_BASE + PMU_SFT_CON,
+			BIT(DBG_NOPWERDWN_L0_EN) |
+			BIT(DBG_NOPWERDWN_L1_EN) |
+			BIT(DBG_NOPWERDWN_L2_EN) |
+			BIT(DBG_NOPWERDWN_L3_EN) |
+			BIT(DBG_NO_PWERDWN_B0_EN) |
+			BIT(DBG_NO_PWERDWN_B1_EN));
+
 	nonboot_cpus_off();
 
 	INFO("%s(%d): pd status %x\n", __func__, __LINE__,
